<p>Virginia has one of the most distinctive economic structures of any state in the country: Northern Virginia, despite being geographically a small part of the state, is the economic engine of the entire region. The federal government, defense contractors, and a massive technology sector centered on data centers (Loudoun County is the data center capital of the world, handling a significant percentage of all global internet traffic) have made Northern Virginia -- Fairfax County, Arlington, Alexandria, Prince William County -- one of the wealthiest regions on the planet. Richmond is a financial hub with major banking operations (Capital One is headquartered in McLean, just outside the city; Freddie Mac and the Federal Reserve Bank of Richmond are both significant presences). Virginia Beach and Hampton Roads support the largest naval complex in the world, with the Naval Station Norfolk and associated defense industries employing tens of thousands.</p>

<p>Virginia uses a graduated income tax with four brackets, topping out at 5.75% on income above $17,000 -- a structure that many consider outdated as the thresholds have not been adjusted for inflation in decades. This generator calculates Virginia's state income tax alongside all federal taxes for a complete, professional pay stub PDF.</p>

<h2>Virginia Income Tax Rates</h2>

<p>Virginia has four income tax brackets for individuals:</p>

<ul>
  <li>2%: $0 to $3,000</li>
  <li>3%: $3,001 to $5,000</li>
  <li>5%: $5,001 to $17,000</li>
  <li>5.75%: Above $17,000</li>
</ul>

<p>The anomalous feature of Virginia's tax brackets is their age: these thresholds have not been adjusted since the late 1980s. As a result, virtually every Virginia worker who earns more than $17,000 annually -- which today means nearly all full-time workers -- pays the top 5.75% marginal rate on the vast majority of their income. In practical terms, Virginia functions almost like a flat-rate state at 5.75% for most workers, with only a small portion of income taxed at the lower rates.</p>

<p>Virginia provides a personal exemption ($930 per exemption in 2024) and a standard deduction ($9,000 for single filers) before applying the tax rates. Even with these adjustments, a Virginia worker earning $60,000 effectively pays approximately 5.4%-5.5% of gross wages in state income tax.</p>

<p>Virginia has no local income taxes. Northern Virginia, despite its wealth and economic complexity, does not impose an additional city or county income tax. All Virginia workers pay the same state rate structure regardless of locality.</p>

<h2>Does Virginia Require Pay Stubs?</h2>

<p>Virginia does not have a state law requiring employers to provide pay stubs to employees. The Virginia Wage Payment Act focuses on ensuring wages are paid on time and in full, but does not mandate the format or provision of written wage statements per pay period.</p>

<p>Large Virginia employers -- defense contractors like Leidos, Booz Allen Hamilton, SAIC, and General Dynamics -- all provide electronic pay stubs through their payroll systems. The federal government (a major Virginia employer through direct federal employment in Northern Virginia) provides detailed leave and earnings statements (LES for military personnel, pay stubs for civilian employees) through the National Finance Center and Defense Finance and Accounting Service systems.</p>

<p>For contractors working on government projects, consultants between engagements, and the significant gig economy in Northern Virginia and Richmond, this generator provides income documentation.</p>

<h2>Pay Stub Requirements in Virginia</h2>

<p>A complete Virginia pay stub should include:</p>

<ul>
  <li>Employer name and address</li>
  <li>Employee name and identification number</li>
  <li>Pay period start and end dates</li>
  <li>Pay date</li>
  <li>Hours worked (hourly employees)</li>
  <li>Gross wages</li>
  <li>Virginia state income tax withheld</li>
  <li>Federal income tax withheld</li>
  <li>Social Security (6.2%) and Medicare (1.45%) withheld</li>
  <li>Any voluntary deductions (Thrift Savings Plan for federal employees, 401(k) for private sector)</li>
  <li>Net pay</li>
  <li>Year-to-date totals</li>
</ul>

<h2>Pay Frequency Laws in Virginia</h2>

<p>Virginia Code § 40.1-29 requires that employers pay wages at regular intervals that are established and communicated to employees in advance. The law does not specify a minimum pay frequency for most employees -- it simply requires that wages be paid at predetermined regular intervals. Most Virginia employers interpret this as requiring at least semi-monthly payment as a practical standard, though monthly payment could technically comply.</p>

<p>Virginia law requires that the employer post its established pay periods and paydays in a conspicuous location at the worksite. Changes to pay frequency must be communicated to employees in advance.</p>

<p>Final paychecks must be paid on or before the next regular payday following termination. Virginia does not require immediate same-day final payment as California does.</p>

<h2>Virginia's Unique Economic Landscape</h2>

<p><strong>Defense contractors and government workers:</strong> The Northern Virginia/DC corridor is the most defense-contractor-dense region in the world. Booz Allen Hamilton, Leidos, General Dynamics IT, ManTech, SAIC, DXC Technology, and hundreds of smaller contractors employ hundreds of thousands of cleared professionals in the intelligence community, defense, and federal civilian technology work. Many defense contractors work as W-2 employees of large contracting firms rather than as direct government employees, and transitions between contracts are common. Workers between contracts need income documentation for the extremely competitive Northern Virginia housing market.</p>

<p><strong>Technology and data centers:</strong> Loudoun County is home to Amazon Web Services, Microsoft Azure, Google, Meta, and dozens of data center operators that handle a disproportionate share of global internet traffic. Data center technicians, network engineers, and cloud infrastructure professionals command high salaries in a market with enormous demand. Amazon's HQ2 in Arlington has also brought thousands of Amazon employees to Northern Virginia, adding to an already sophisticated tech workforce.</p>

<p><strong>Agriculture in rural Virginia:</strong> Away from the Northern Virginia and Richmond metros, Virginia has a substantial agricultural sector: poultry processing (Tyson, Pilgrim's Pride), wine production (Charlottesville area is a growing wine region), and traditional farming. Agricultural workers in the Shenandoah Valley and Southside Virginia have very different income documentation needs than defense contractors in Tysons Corner.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions for Virginia Workers</h2>

<h3>Virginia's top tax bracket starts at $17,000. Does that mean I'm in the top bracket on almost all my income?</h3>
<p>Yes. Because the $17,000 threshold was set decades ago and never inflation-adjusted, any Virginia worker earning more than $17,000 annually -- which is essentially every full-time worker at or above Virginia's minimum wage -- pays 5.75% on most of their taxable income. The lower brackets (2%, 3%, 5%) only apply to the first $17,000 of taxable income. For a worker earning $60,000, the blended effective state tax rate is approximately 5.5-5.6% after the standard deduction, with most income taxed at 5.75%. Virginia has been discussing bracket modernization in the legislature but as of 2024, the brackets remain unchanged.</p>

<h3>I'm a defense contractor with a security clearance who works in Northern Virginia. Does my clearance affect my tax situation?</h3>
<p>No. Security clearances do not affect income tax calculation or pay stub requirements. Your gross pay, withholding, and net pay are calculated identically to any other Virginia employee. Classified compensation may have specific rules around documentation for security reasons, but tax reporting obligations are unchanged. If you work at a Sensitive Compartmented Information Facility (SCIF) for a defense contractor, your W-2 and pay stubs accurately reflect your wages regardless of the classified nature of your work.</p>

<h3>I'm a federal government employee in Northern Virginia. How does my LES differ from a pay stub?</h3>
<p>Federal civilian employees receive a Leave and Earnings Statement (LES) that serves the same function as a private sector pay stub. The LES shows your gross pay, all deductions (federal income tax, TSP contributions, health insurance premiums, FEHB contributions, and federal employee retirement deductions), and net pay. The LES format is standardized across all federal agencies. Virginia income tax is withheld from your federal salary and shown on your LES just as it would be on any Virginia employer's pay stub. If you need documentation in a format that non-government landlords or lenders recognize more easily, you can use your most recent LES as equivalent to a pay stub.</p>

<h3>Does Virginia have any state disability insurance or paid family leave?</h3>
<p>Virginia does not have state disability insurance or paid family leave programs funded through employee payroll deductions. Virginia's payroll deductions for employees are limited to the state income tax (graduated 2%-5.75%) and federal taxes. Workers who need paid leave for disability or family care must rely on employer-provided benefits or private insurance. Virginia has discussed paid family leave legislation but had not enacted a mandatory program as of 2024.</p>

<h3>I work at Amazon HQ2 in Arlington. How do RSUs affect my pay stubs?</h3>
<p>Restricted Stock Units (RSUs) vest over time and are taxable as ordinary income when they vest -- they are added to your gross wages on the pay stub for the pay period in which they vest. Amazon's payroll system automatically calculates the taxable value of vesting RSUs (typically using the fair market value on the vesting date) and adds this to your gross pay for that period. This can create a significant spike in one paycheck's gross pay and withholding. The resulting stub looks different from your base salary stubs -- the gross pay will be much higher than usual for RSU vesting periods. When providing pay documentation to lenders or landlords, be prepared to explain RSU income and note that it may not recur at the same level every period. For mortgage qualification, lenders typically want a two-year RSU history to count it as regular income.</p>

